snippet.title: Paris 18th Arrondissement - 20 in 20 Day 18 - Montmartre and More in the 18th of Paris
snippet.description:
Paris' 18th arrondissement is my favorite place on Earth, really - Montmartre just feels so homey, chill, and separate in so many ways. Grab my guide to Paris here: http://bit.ly/ParisVloggersGuide to find the places I visited (whether successfully or not 😂) and have yourself a great time in Montmartre and beyond in the 18th arrondissement of Paris.

Help me make better videos at http://patreon.com/jayswanson and then find me on the internet in all of the usual spots:


More swag here:
http://bit.ly/ShirtOfTheMonth (shirts and hat)
http://bit.ly/JaysGearList (my gear and books)
https://gum.co/camerafour (Disposable Camera Four digital scans)

Follow me here:
http://twitter.com/jayonaboat
http://instagram.com/jayswanson

Music by:

My name is Jay Swanson - I'm an American writer living in Paris on an artist visa and hoping to make the city of light my home base - at least for the foreseeable future. I write science-fiction and fantasy, vlog daily, and love pizza a little too much.

Links below to Amazon are affiliate links - meaning if you click through them and buy something, I'll get some pennies. Thanks! (The FTC wants me to tell you that up front)

FAQ:
How long have you lived in France? On and off for over two years.

What do you miss most about ho- NACHOS

You're always talking about living on some ship. WHAT SHIP? - I made a "Draw My Life" video that explains a lot here: https://youtu.be/-MrvL37jTKM

Where are you from originally? - Pullman, Washington - a small university/agricultural town near Idaho (and yes, the potatoes are amazing).

What do you film with? - I've made a lot of changes recently, but I try to keep my gear list up to date if you want to see what I use and buy some for yourself: http://bit.ly/JaysGearList

What do you edit with? - Adobe Premiere - it's pretty much all I've ever used since high school.

Aren't you ever freaked out by leaving your camera behind to film yourself? - Yep. But not too badly - I tend to be careful when I do.

Why are you living in #Paris? - Because I've always wanted to; I feel at home here: https://youtu.be/4Vivf6MqMxQ

Do you speak French? Oui. https://youtu.be/va1QjaHgij8

You talk a lot about the books you're working on, what are they about? - They're sci-fi (and fantasy) and I've got a decent pitch for you here: https://youtu.be/W2bKt4_Tp4E

Do you make money off YouTube? - Ha, no. I wish. It took me over 500 videos to make my first total $100 off adsense. I think it will slowly change, but VERY slowly.

I really enjoy your videos, how can I support you? - The easiest and best way to support me is through Patreon, where you can pitch in as little as $1/mo to help me make better videos: http://patreon.com/jayswanson

I don't trust this Patreon thing - can I just paypal you? - Here's my ko-fi if that's your thing (and coffee is your game): https://ko-fi.com/jayswanson

But I want to send you something tangible! - I do have a wishlist on Amazon, though it's a bit complicated with the international shipping situation. This is the US one: http://amzn.to/2ykS9Ux

And here's the French wishlist: http://bit.ly/JaysFrenchWishList

Thanks for watching!

comments.textDisplay:
LOVE THIS VIDEO !!
This area has been my neighborhood for several years now and boy you did it justice !! Great job of balancing the must-do tourist bits of Sacre Cœur area as well as more off the beaten path parts of the hill aka my favorite parts, as a resident. This video is pitch perfect.
Bummed I missed seeing you around on the wheelie yesterday!!
And yes to more videos on the 18th!

comments.textDisplay:
Travel tip for anyone wanting to ride the Funiculaire up and down the hill: it’s a part of the public transport network. You can use a Carnet ticket, your Paris Visite, or your Navigo Card. It counts as a journey in zone 1.

Oh, and Howard Jones shot a lot of the video for his 1983 song What Is Love in the 18eme.

https://youtu.be/w34vnz_LEX4

comments.textDisplay:
OMG. Is a bit sad that my trip happened before this series. You have such a great way to show stuff that we missed when running around Paris. I totally missed Sacre Coeur behind Le Consulat coming up the stairs. Checking my photos, I can see one with my wife where there is the tip of the cupula creeping out, but I should have framed it much better. BTW, walking down from Le Consulat we passed alongside the vineyard. We weren't looking for it, but we heard about it, and I have pictures now. Great find.

comments.textDisplay: As an American who use to live in Paris; I got use to having most things closed on Sunday’s
comments.textOriginal: As an American who use to live in Paris; I got use to having most things closed on Sunday’s

replies.textDisplay:
+Jay Swanson it's changing though ! I used to live in Shanghai, where you virtually can't walk ten minutes without going past a 24/7 convenient store, so I had some trouble adjusting when I came back, but it's been a year since they passed a law authorizing shops and malls to open up on Sunday within the boundaries of 10 predefined zones within the city limits (there are 21 such zones in the country).

All food shops are allowed (and have been so for many years) to open on Sunday until 1pm, so there's usually at least a bakery and a Monoprix, Franprix or other such shop open in every small neighbourhood, especially around metro stations.

I briefly lived close to Pyrénées in the 19th arrondissement and pretty much all the shops on Belleville street (which is not in any of the 10 zones) were open on Sunday, with the notable exception of the optical shop. I guess the other shops either had special waivers from the Préfecture, or were operating illegally (maybe the smaller ones ?). They were open anyhow.

I now live in the 15th arrondissement between Vaugirard and Volontaires, and I have 2 small supermarkets, 3 mid-sized supermarkets, 1 rather big Monoprix, 1 bakery/pastry shop, 1 "creamery" (delicatessen ? They sell cheese), 2 greengrocers, 1 fishmonger, 1 laundromat, 2 butchershops/rôtisseries, 2 Asian takeaway shops, an equine butcher's, and 1 "tabac-PMU" (tobacco and lottery and bookies shop) that are open within a 5-minute-walk radius. But only 'til 1pm. After that the available offer shrinks down to 1 small Franprix supermarket.

You know what they say : the early bird... is not me so I always go to the small Franprix. ^^'
Who wants worms anyway ?

When I lived in Montpellier there was only one shop open on Sunday morning in the whole downtown/midtown area (a Monoprix on Place de la Comédie). Those were dark days, when Sundays were plan-or-starve traps haha

replies.textDisplay:
Ohlalaaaaa - il y a des endroits peu attirants au nord-est de Paris depuis plus d'un siècle, c'est un héritage de la révolution industrielle... C'est pourtant connu !

"À Paris, la bise souffle principalement de l’Ouest vers l’Est. Par conséquent, les quartiers ouest sont moins exposés que d’autres aux fumées domestiques et industrielles. Et il y en a eu ! Des fabriques en tous genres, des tanneries et des fonderies aux hautes cheminées odorantes. Et aussi des industries"
Ces quartiers ont généralement moins d'intérêt touristique en dehors de Montmartre, Pigalle (qui est un carrefour de la prostitution, de l'alcool et de la drogue depuis plus d'un siècle) et les Buttes Chaumont, avec moins de monuments, belles églises, édifices imposants, musées internationaux etc. Parce que les ouvriers n'avaient pas ce genre de luxe.

Ma mère est bretonne, tout ce qu'il y a de plus blanc, blonde aux yeux verts, née juste après la guerre d'un marin et d'une paysanne, et où cette étudiante pauvre vivait-elle à Paris en 1970 ? Marx Dormoy. Pourquoi ? Parce qu'elle était pauvre.
Aujourd'hui, l'extrême est du 17e, une partie des 18e, 19e et 20e arrondissements et l'extrême Nord du 2e sont toujours les quartiers les moins chers, où vivent les Parisiens les plus pauvres, dont les populations d'origine subsaharienne et maghrébine. Ils n'ont rien de particulièrement intéressant pour des touristes, comme le Bronx pour des Français...
